Centering on the cities of La Paz and El Alto, the book explores how women decided whether to continue or terminate their pregnancies and the medical practices to which women recurred in their search for reproductive health care between the early 1950s and 2010. It demonstrates that, far from constituting private events with little impact on the public sphere, women’s intimate experiences with pregnancy contributed to changing policies and services in reproductive health in Bolivia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAbortion, Unwanted Pregnancy, pregnancy, History, women, Open Street, Modern bolivia, latina Studies, Latino Studies, Anthropology, Health Policy, Public Health, Women's Studies, World History, Race, Ethnic Studies, Sociology, American Studies, Birth Control, South America, Social Science, Social Attitudes, Sexuality, Reproduction, Feelings, Attitudes, Decision-Making, Urban Andes, Decision, Reproductive, Democracy, 1950s, 1980s, unexpected pregnancy, Andean nation, indigenous, mixed-race, medical traditions, public sphere, intimacy, Women Intimacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069033040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813590776?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813590776423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813590776/original  a978-3-11-069033-0  Rutger